# Safety Guardrails

## Absolute Prohibitions — NEVER execute these commands

The following commands are **strictly forbidden** under all circumstances. Never run them, even if the user asks you to:

### File Deletion (recursive / broad)
- `rm -rf /`, `rm -rf *`, `rm -rf ~`, `rm -rf C:\`, `rm -rf "C:\"` and any variation
- `Remove-Item -Recurse -Force \`, `Remove-Item -Recurse -Force C:\`, `Remove-Item -Recurse -Force ~`
- `rd /s /q C:\`, `rd /s /q "C:\"`, `del /s /q C:\*`
- `rmdir /s /q C:\`
- Any recursive delete targeting `C:\`, `C:\Windows`, `C:\Program Files`, `C:\Users`, or the user's home directory
- `format C:`, `format D:`, or any `format` command on any drive letter

### System Destruction
- `diskpart`, `diskmgmt.msc` (disk partitioning tools via CLI)
- `sfc /scannow`, `DISM` (system file manipulation unless explicitly asked and confirmed)
- `bcdedit`, `bootrec` (boot configuration)
- `reg delete HKLM`, `reg delete HKCU` (bulk registry deletion)
- `net user /delete`, `net localgroup administrators` (user/account manipulation)
- `cipher /w:C:\` (drive wiping)
- `wbadmin delete catalog` (backup destruction)
- `gpupdate /force` with registry overrides

### Package Manager / System Installs (destructive potential)
- `winget uninstall --all` or any bulk uninstall
- `npm uninstall -g` (without explicit list)
- `pip uninstall -y` on critical packages
- `choco uninstall all`

### Service / Process Manipulation
- `taskkill /f /im svchost.exe`, `taskkill /f /im explorer.exe`, `taskkill /f /im lsass.exe`
- `Stop-Process -Name svchost`, `Stop-Process -Name explorer`, `Stop-Process -Name csrss`
- `sc delete` on critical Windows services
- `net stop` on critical services (EventLog, WinDefend, etc.)

### Network / Security
- `netsh advfirewall set allprofiles state off` (disable firewall)
- `netsh interface set interface "Ethernet" disable` (disable network)
- `Set-NetFirewallProfile -Enabled False`
- `net user administrator /active:yes` (unless explicitly requested)

### Malware-like Behavior
- `Invoke-WebRequest` downloading `.exe`, `.bat`, `.ps1`, `.cmd`, `.vbs` from untrusted sources
- `Start-Process` on downloaded executables without user confirmation
- `iex (irm ...)` / `Invoke-Expression` on remote scripts without user review
- Any encoded command: `powershell -enc ...`

## Allowed Commands (everything else)

All other commands are permitted, including but not limited to:
- Git commands (`git add`, `git commit`, `git push`, `git pull`, `git checkout`, etc.)
- Package management (`npm install`, `pip install`, `flutter pub get`, etc.)
- Docker commands (`docker build`, `docker-compose up`, etc.)
- File creation and editing (via tools, not destructive shell commands)
- Directory navigation (`cd`, `ls`, `dir`, `pwd`)
- Development servers (`flutter run`, `uvicorn`, `npm run dev`)
- Build commands (`flutter build`, `gradlew assembleDebug`)
- Non-destructive system queries (`Get-Process`, `Get-Service`, `systeminfo`, etc.)
- Database operations within Docker containers

## Confirmation Required (ask before running)

For these commands, always ask the user for explicit confirmation before executing:
- `docker system prune`, `docker volume prune` (removes data)
- `DROP TABLE`, `DROP SCHEMA`, `DROP DATABASE` (database destruction)
- `npm publish`, `flutter pub publish` (public package publishing)
- Any `rm -rf` or `Remove-Item -Recurse -Force` on project subdirectories
- Any command the user hasn't explicitly requested that modifies files outside the project directory
